{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d863818-37b3-43ab-9ca5-a46719626dcd","content":"This is **xUnit v3** on **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (MTP). Use the native `--filter-class` option:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter-class Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests\n```\n\nOr with the traditional `--filter` syntax:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter-class` form is preferred for MTP — it's an exact match on the fully qualified class name.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed86fc49-5551-4cf5-b7ff-4c2552322b20","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is xUnit.net v3 with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true`, which means it's using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). For MTP with xUnit v3, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor xUnit v3 on MTP, you use `--filter-class` to filter by class name:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter-class Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests\n```\n\nOr with the VSTest compatibility filter:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. \n\nWith `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true`, `dotnet test` routes through MTP, and for xUnit v3 the native approach is using `--filter-class` for class-level filtering, though `--filter` with VSTest-compatible expressions also works as a fallback option.","outputTokens":709},"id":"dcb540dd-a30f-43f0-89c7-b2b4e81cf08c","timestamp":"2026-04-07T15:56:48.949Z","parentId":"329bf8d2-2a67-4f4b-979a-a47dcbc8b375"}
